1
00:00:09,685 --> 00:00:12,453
I see why they call this place
"Hell On Wheels."

2
00:00:12,487 --> 00:00:14,055
Rough men, loose women,

3
00:00:14,089 --> 00:00:16,223
whiskey, sin, and guns.

4
00:00:16,258 --> 00:00:19,026
It ain't
a church social, ma'am.

5
00:00:19,061 --> 00:00:20,661
I'm not sure your bosses
at Credit Mobilier

6
00:00:20,696 --> 00:00:23,698
would want me to put <i>that</i>
in the newspaper.

7
00:00:23,732 --> 00:00:26,333
What is it that holds you to
this enterprise, Mr. Bohannon?

8
00:00:26,368 --> 00:00:27,635
Every piece of steel we lay

9
00:00:27,669 --> 00:00:29,637
puts us closer
to somewheres else.

10
00:00:29,671 --> 00:00:31,872
That's about all I can say.

11
00:00:31,907 --> 00:00:36,010
So it's more personal
than just laying rail.

12
00:00:36,044 --> 00:00:39,580
You're the writer.
Ho!

13
00:00:39,614 --> 00:00:41,915
Mr. Bohannon,
people of this country

14
00:00:41,950 --> 00:00:45,152
believe the railroad is robbing
the National Treasury.

15
00:00:45,186 --> 00:00:47,521
My job is to dissuade my readers
of that notion.

16
00:00:47,555 --> 00:00:50,591
Unfortunately,
our brief interview

17
00:00:50,625 --> 00:00:52,326
was not enough to dissuade me.

18
00:00:52,360 --> 00:00:55,095
And it ain't my job
to fix what people think.

19
00:00:55,129 --> 00:00:56,863
In fact, it is.

20
00:00:56,898 --> 00:00:59,199
You are the face of the
Transcontinental Railroad now.

21
00:00:59,233 --> 00:01:01,935
And either this is
a brave and noble endeavor,

22
00:01:01,969 --> 00:01:04,104
or it's Sodom and Gomorrah.

23
00:01:04,138 --> 00:01:07,707
Which is it?

24
00:01:07,742 --> 00:01:09,442
The sooner you help me
accurately report

25
00:01:09,477 --> 00:01:10,944
what's going on out here,
the sooner I can leave

26
00:01:10,978 --> 00:01:13,680
and make both our lives
less miserable.

27
00:01:13,714 --> 00:01:15,949
And for the record,
I covered the war '63 to '65.

28
00:01:15,983 --> 00:01:18,418
I know the difference between
hell and a church social.

29
00:01:18,452 --> 00:01:21,187
What more you need to see?

30
00:01:21,222 --> 00:01:25,759
Everything.

31
00:01:25,793 --> 00:01:28,094
Come on then.

32
00:01:28,128 --> 00:01:30,363
♪ That I ever did see
♪ that I ever did see

33
00:01:30,397 --> 00:01:32,765
♪ she was born
in Jackson, baby ♪

34
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:34,267
♪ raised in New Orleans

35
00:01:34,301 --> 00:01:36,803
Grading crews work ahead
of the tie-layers.

36
00:01:36,837 --> 00:01:39,272
100 miles west,
surveyors lay out the route.

37
00:01:39,306 --> 00:01:41,741
- How many men do you have?
- Near 3,000.

38
00:01:41,775 --> 00:01:43,910
Work six days a week,
sunup, sundown.

39
00:01:43,944 --> 00:01:46,946
$1.50 a day.
Them's good wages.

40
00:01:46,980 --> 00:01:48,948
How many miles do you make
a day?

41
00:01:48,982 --> 00:01:52,251
Two now,
weather and Indians permittin'.

42
00:01:55,088 --> 00:01:56,989
Rust eaters lay the rails.

43
00:01:57,024 --> 00:01:59,558
Walking boss makes sure
the gauge is right.

44
00:01:59,593 --> 00:02:02,995
Spiker teams secure the rails
to the ground.

45
00:02:03,029 --> 00:02:05,297
Fish-plates tie them together.

46
00:02:05,332 --> 00:02:07,333
3 swings of the hammer
per spike,

47
00:02:07,367 --> 00:02:11,003
10 spikes per rail,
400 rails to a mile,

48
00:02:11,037 --> 00:02:14,039
1,500 miles to Sacramento.

49
00:02:16,543 --> 00:02:18,110
Do you really believe
you can win the race

50
00:02:18,144 --> 00:02:19,812
against the Central Pacific
to build this road?

51
00:02:19,846 --> 00:02:21,347
Wouldn't be here otherwise.

52
00:02:21,381 --> 00:02:22,915
You think you can do it

53
00:02:22,949 --> 00:02:24,450
without Thomas Durant's
political connections?

54
00:02:24,484 --> 00:02:26,652
Without his money,
his ego to drive it on?

55
00:02:26,686 --> 00:02:30,189
Well, here I stand,
and here he don't.

56
00:02:30,223 --> 00:02:34,626
- Excuse me.
- One more question.

57
00:02:34,661 --> 00:02:37,396
Why you?

58
00:02:47,373 --> 00:02:49,941
Each car sleeps 60 men.

59
00:02:49,976 --> 00:02:52,944
Keeps them out of the weather
and close to the work.

60
00:02:52,979 --> 00:02:55,981
Lady coming through.

61
00:02:59,852 --> 00:03:02,120
Who designed these cars?

62
00:03:02,154 --> 00:03:03,388
Mostly me.

63
00:03:06,192 --> 00:03:09,728
Yeah, I'm still working out
the ventilation.

64
00:03:09,762 --> 00:03:11,463
Mmhmm.

65
00:03:11,497 --> 00:03:13,064
Two weeks ago, these men
were starving, out of work,

66
00:03:13,098 --> 00:03:15,033
straight off the boats
in New York.

67
00:03:15,067 --> 00:03:16,401
My newspaper has reported
Irish labor bosses

68
00:03:16,435 --> 00:03:18,069
conscripting them out here
for a fee.

69
00:03:18,103 --> 00:03:20,905
How is that any different
from indentured servitude?

70
00:03:20,940 --> 00:03:22,974
Union Pacific offers
free rail passage

71
00:03:23,008 --> 00:03:25,009
and a week's wages on arrival.

72
00:03:25,044 --> 00:03:26,711
We got more applicants
than we got work.

73
00:03:26,745 --> 00:03:28,346
Really?

74
00:03:28,380 --> 00:03:31,082
Your idea again?

75
00:03:31,116 --> 00:03:35,853
Didn't much care for the labor
bosses I met in New York.

76
00:03:47,132 --> 00:03:48,432
New cemetery runs
from the sawmill

77
00:03:48,467 --> 00:03:50,401
up to the Ridge line.

78
00:03:50,435 --> 00:03:52,169
Ain't a day goes by
we don't put some one or two

79
00:03:52,204 --> 00:03:56,941
in the ground up there,
most from railroad mishaps.

80
00:03:56,975 --> 00:03:59,209
And the others?

81
00:03:59,244 --> 00:04:03,614
Spare time mishaps.

82
00:04:03,648 --> 00:04:08,452
Is that where the fair-haired
maiden of the west is buried?

83
00:04:11,556 --> 00:04:14,858
No, she's buried in
a wild flower field she liked.

84
00:04:14,893 --> 00:04:17,527
- Did you know her?
- A bit.

85
00:04:17,562 --> 00:04:18,962
Well, you must've known her
better than that

86
00:04:18,997 --> 00:04:21,365
if you knew where she wanted
to be buried.

87
00:04:21,399 --> 00:04:22,633
Mrs. Bell should've left
Hell On Wheels

88
00:04:22,667 --> 00:04:24,534
when she had the chance.

89
00:04:24,569 --> 00:04:26,970
This ain't no place for a lady,

90
00:04:27,004 --> 00:04:30,307
less'n she's a whore.

91
00:04:30,341 --> 00:04:32,309
I can assure you,
Mr. Bohannon,

92
00:04:32,343 --> 00:04:35,045
I am neither a lady
nor a whore.

93
00:04:35,079 --> 00:04:36,613
Figured you'd have to be
a little bit of both

94
00:04:36,647 --> 00:04:38,148
being a newspaper woman.

95
00:04:38,182 --> 00:04:40,050
Get outta here.

96
00:04:40,084 --> 00:04:42,385
Huh.

97
00:04:42,420 --> 00:04:43,620
You figured wrong.

98
00:04:48,459 --> 00:04:50,894
You Bohannon?

99
00:04:50,928 --> 00:04:53,496
I am.

100
00:04:55,666 --> 00:04:57,333
Keep your railroad
off my property.

101
00:04:57,368 --> 00:05:00,370
I won't tell you again.

102
00:05:08,045 --> 00:05:10,580
Where'd they come from?

103
00:05:10,614 --> 00:05:13,449
No idea.

104
00:05:13,484 --> 00:05:15,685
Train for Omaha leaves
in an hour.

105
00:05:15,719 --> 00:05:18,721
I expect you won't
wanna miss it.

